There are 500K products and 2M audit logs. How do I make these efficient?

data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`** — they translate directly to SQL `UPDATE`/`DELETE` without loading a single entity into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk UPDATE — single SQL statement, zero entities loaded
var cutoffDate = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6);
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < cutoffDate)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk DELETE — single SQL statement, zero entities loaded
var logCutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1);
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is faster:**

| | Original | `ExecuteUpdate/Delete` |
|---|---|---|
| SQL roundtrips | 2 (SELECT + UPDATE/DELETE) | 1 |
| Entities loaded | 500K / 2M | **0** |
| Memory | GBs of tracked objects | negligible |
| Change tracker | processes every entity | **bypassed** |

**Caveats to be aware of:**

- These bypass the change tracker — any already-loaded entities in the `DbContext` won't reflect the changes. Call these before querying, or re-query afterward.
- If the 2M audit log delete causes lock escalation / long transactions, batch it:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```

This deletes in 10K-row chunks to avoid holding a massive lock.
